I don't think the workaround @syranide outlined will work in all the necessary cases. For example, I don't believe you can do:

```
var MyButton = React.createClass({
        displayName: 'MyButton',
        componentDidMount: function() {
            this.getDOMNode().setAttribute('is', 'my-button');
        },
        render: function() {
            return React.createElement('button', $.extend({}, this.props));
        }
    });
```

And have it be properly upgraded as a "my-button" custom element. I assume because we're setting the `is` attribute after the element is created and placed in the document. I'd be happy to hear if there's another way to deal with this particular case.

Here is the solution i came accross https://github.com/SimpliField/react/commit/8861a9461c0f4dbac2c6dfb1bfe71a4d8c5fc356.

It allowed me to inject custom attributes for my needs with this piece of code:

``` js
var HTMLDOMLegacyPropertyConfig = {
  isCustomAttribute: function(attributeName) {
    return -1 !== [
      'align', 'bgcolor', 'border'
     ].indexOf(attributeName);
  },
  Properties: {
    align: null,
    bgcolor: null,
    border: null
  },
  DOMAttributeNames: {
  },
  DOMPropertyNames: {
  }
};

var React = require('react');

// Allow custom/legacy attributes for mail templates
React.Injection.DOMProperty.injectDOMPropertyConfig(HTMLDOMLegacyPropertyConfig);
```

Any better way to inject this ? If no, any plan on exposing ReactInjection on the React main object ?

I received some initial feedback the the subscribable properties map (and the `propertyName` parameters passed to the config functions) may be too confusing, and that a single-subscribable-property approach might be better.

This _would_ simplify the config functions. For example, the configuration for a single subscribable property could be simplified to something like:
```js
createComponent(
  {
    property: 'textInput',
    getSubscriptionValue: (props: Props) => props.textInput.value,
    subscribe: (
      props: Props,
      valueChangedCallback: (value: any) => void
    ): Function => {
      const onChange = event => valueChangedCallback(props.textInput.value);
      props.textInput.addEventListener("change", onChange);
      return onChange;
    },
    unsubscribe: (props: Props, subscription: Function) => {
      props.textInput.removeEventListener("change", subscription);
    }
  },
  InnerComponent
);
```

And it might also allow me to support Flow typing (something I don't know how to do with the mapping approach).

Does anyone have thoughts on this?

### A note about the `property` key

I'm not sure how some people will feel about the `property` key in this configuration object, but the HOC/mixin needs _some way_ of knowing when the subscribable property has changed.

One alternative could be a `hasChanged` function that receives `oldProps` and `newProps` parameters and returns a boolean.

Ah, was just thinking that might be a better name than `getData` if there's only a single subscribed property.

So for example...
```js
function getDataFor(subscribable, propertyName) {
  switch (propertyName) {
    case "followerStore":
      return subscribable.getValue();
    case "scrollContainer":
      return subscriber.scrollTop;
  }
}
```

Could be simplified to...
```js
function getSubscriptionValue(props) {
  return props.scrollContainer.scrollTop;
}
```

Probably we can save our souls (and types) and follow `createStuff` pattern like `createRef` and `createContext` (and maybe `createState` in the future). @bvaughn what do you think about this?

```js
const Subscription = createComponent({
  getSubscriptionValue: props => {
    return props.textInput.value
  },
  subscribe: (props, valueChangedCallback) => {
    const onChange = event => valueChangedCallback(props.textInput.value);
    props.textInput.addEventListener("change", onChange);
    return onChange;
  },
  unsubscribe: (props, subscription) => {
    props.textInput.removeEventListener("change", subscription);
  }
})

const App = ({ textInput }) => (
  <Subscription textInput={textInput}>
    {value =>
      <InnerComponent textInput={value} />
    }
  </Subscription>
)
```
